## 100% Free Hosting Alternatives 

Since you prefer a completely free deployment pipeline without any Google Cloud billing friction, I have removed the Firebase configurations and strongly recommend the following platforms instead. Both of these are industry standards and **cost $0 for personal portfolios**.

### Option 1: Vercel (Recommended & Easiest)
Vercel is the company that built Next.js, and they offer deeply integrated, zero-config free hosting for personal projects.

> [!TIP]
> **To deploy with Vercel:**
> 1. Push this workspace code to a new GitHub repository.
> 2. Create a free account at [Vercel](https://vercel.com).
> 3. Click **Add New Project** and import your GitHub repository.
> 4. Vercel will automatically detect that it's a Next.js app, configure everything, build it, and give you a free `your-name.vercel.app` domain. 

### Option 2: GitHub Pages
If you just want to host it entirely natively on GitHub without creating another account, you can use GitHub Pages via incredibly straightforward GitHub Actions. Note that if you don't attach a custom domain, you might need extra configuration (like setting a `basePath`), so Vercel is heavily preferred for ease of use.

## Running the Application Locally
Because Node/NPM are required to run the development server, you will need to:
1. Ensure Node.js is installed on your Windows machine if you want to preview the app before pushing to GitHub. ([Download Node.js](https://nodejs.org/))
2. Open a fresh terminal and run:
```bash
npm install
npm run dev
```

The site will be available locally on `localhost:3000`. You can interact with the deep aesthetics and works grid right away!
